segments.text: Who the other general officers were, he took to Africa with him, but I know that Delmar Dutton was my immediate commanding general.
Now, were you in at all on the planning of the invasion of North Africa, Operation Torch?
I was in on the planning for the supply maintenance.
Part of it.
Part of it.
In fact, I did all the thickness shovel work on that.
I had an awful time.
The telephone system in England was horrible.
It was so bad that I appointed my brightest, best lieutenant to do nothing but get me telephone numbers.
I called in all over England trying to get a hold of these people and tell them what to do.
I couldn't spend all my time trying to get a number, trying to get a line through.
It was horrible.
So as far as supply and maintenance, was that the biggest problem, or were there other large problems?
That was the only problem I had, and I was the man that had to put it on.
I had some pretty good help.
Did you get enough supplies?
Yeah, we got everybody fixed up.
We didn't actually have enough transportation.
We were always short of transportation, Jeeps and trucks.
Down in Africa, we were still short.
Sicily was short.
What about aircraft?
Did you have enough aircraft?
I wasn't worried about the aircraft because that wasn't part of my business.
They had lost quite a number of C-47s in the landing in Algiers.
They went on there with paratroopers and knights, you know, and they landed all over the place.
Lost quite a number of aircraft, but that wasn't my, that wasn't my, my job was parts, supply parts, gasoline.
and maintenance crews, depot crews, and so forth.
Did you get enough gasoline to them?
Get enough what?
Gasoline.
Yeah, it came in a 55 gallon drum, and some of it came in a 5 gallon jerry can, as they called them.
I had a
Gasoline dumps several different places around North Africa.
The enemy had come over and dropped a few incendiary bombs while they could burn up a lot of gasoline, but they didn't do it.
They didn't know where they were located?
I don't know why they, I never could figure out why they did this and that.
When did you land in North Africa?
Me personally?
I think it was 18th of November.
I think the invasion was the 11th of November.
So you came about a week later.
Yeah.
I went down by C-47 Flying Fortress back in the bomb compartment.
What were your feelings about finally getting into the War Theater?
Well, I was glad to get there.
I was so happy to get out of Washington, and anywhere would have been alright.
Now, when you got down to Altiers and North Africa, one of the major questions was if the French were going to, how the French in North Africa were going to react.
Yeah, and I lost a good friend, Lieutenant Cross, C-R-E-W.
I guess he was a colonel at that time.
He could speak French.
I know at Casablanca was where the French were concentrated.
And I guess he volunteered.
He said, I can speak French.
Let me go ashore and talk to him.
He walked ashore, and the French, some trigger-happy Frenchman shot him and killed him.
He never did get to talk to him.
But the French capitulated right away.
Yeah.
And did they fight with you?
Of course, De Gaulle went down.
Oh, I don't know.
I guess there were some French units in Eisenhower's, in Eisenhower's down in Africa at that time.
Sure, yeah.
I think he may have had some French units in his command.
Did you ever get to see De Gaulle?
No.
And, of course, and Eisenhower was down there at that time, did you?
I saw a picture in there with you and Eisenhower.
Yeah, well, I didn't know him then.
Oh, okay.
Well, when did you meet the general?
I may have met him in London when we were laying on the invasion, but I'm not sure.
But those pictures were taken when I was commanding general at Kelly Field, and he came down there.
He was chief of staff there.
This was after the war.
Yeah, 1946.
Yeah, and he came down there to make an inspection for the veteran.
Now, at this time, the German Air Force was still rather powerful.
What were your thoughts in the Air Force about the Luftwaffe?
Well, they used to come over and bomb.
They bombed the harbor in Iran and dropped a few bombs.
One time I was in Algiers and they were bombing a harbor there.
I was in the hotel.
Traces of bullets go right by my window at these Jaron planes.
I stood that for a little while and I decided I'd go down to the basement where the air raid shelter was and I got down there
A few entertainers down there from this country who were entertaining the troops.
They were being entertained that night.
They weren't doing any entertaining.
There weren't many people down there in the bomb shelter.
What did you think of the quality of the German Air Force?
Well, they were, I didn't know too much about them because I wasn't in the fighting business.
Right, right.
But from what I gathered talking to my friends, why they're a pretty hot bunch.
Pretty good.
They knew their business.
Now at this time, or after this time, you got to know General Mark Clark, is that right?
Yeah.
Could you describe him?
He was a pompous, ultra-conceited ass, but don't quote me.
Well, he's long gone, so.
Oh, he got his start by, I guess he could speak French.
He got in, or maybe Italian.
Anyway, he got
He went ashore somewhere and talked to French, I believe, and he started promoting himself then.
He must have had a real bent for promoting himself and maybe a good publicity man because next thing you know he's a general.
Where is he?
He's way back here halfway from Moran to Casablanca, sitting there.
hundreds of miles from where the fighting is, and he's parading.
He's formed himself an armed honor guard, dressed him up in beautiful uniforms.
As far as he was concerned, there wasn't a war anywhere in Europe, and he was showing the natives how the West Point parade would
be hell if it was over there.
He called up, he had his chief of staff call me at Iran there and wanted, I don't know, some sort of fancy stuff.
And I said, I don't have that in stock.
Well, get it for us.
So I said, I'm not in the business of getting stuff for you anyway.
I'm in the business of supplying the Air Force here.
keeping supplies and maintenance for the 12th Air Force.
Well, that didn't set very well with the colonel, he called me.
I guess it didn't set very well with Mark Clark either.
What did he want?
I've forgotten.
I didn't even, it was something I needed when
necessary to win the war, and that's all we were thinking about, was winning the war, you see.
I knew it wasn't necessary.
I knew what he was doing back there.
He was just having himself a ball with this beautiful arm of honor guard that he formed, and impressing the natives.
What a great man he was.
You can have him.
Okay.
What about Montgomery?
I never met Montgomery, but from what I've heard, he was the same type.
But you never came in contact then with the British in North Africa?
He's what?
Did you ever come in contact with the British Army in North Africa?
Some of the British officers, yes.
They were all very fine, very cooperative.
For instance, in Sicily,
I had trouble with the quartermaster, General Eisenhower's quartermaster.
When we went into Sicily, the quartermaster of the Army was charged with furnishing us food, trucks, and things like that, hardware.
Never could get any trucks out of the quartermaster.
I unloaded a shipload of trucks for him one time in Iran on the promise I'd get 10% of them.
And son of a bitch went back on his word and didn't give me any.
And over in Sicily, I went over from Jaila, I think, at that time.
I flew up to Palermo, where General Patton was in charge.
I talked to his quartermaster about
getting food for the Air Force.
We weren't getting any rations.
And so and so said, well, I just have dock space enough to unload food for the ground troops.
The Air Force will have to get the food somewhere else.
Can you imagine that?
Gee whiz.
Yeah.
So I borrowed 60,000 rations from the British.
They were very cooperative.
You mean their own army wouldn't help you, but the British would?
The British would, yeah.
The British helped me out on trucks when I couldn't get them from our own quartermaster.
The British were very cooperative with me.
Now in 1943, we invaded Sicily, and you moved from North Africa to Sicily in a new job commanding the 51st Troop Carrier Wing.
Well that was after I'd been in Sicily for some time.
So you moved up to Sicily then with the 12th Air Force and you were still in supply and maintenance.
Advanced echelon of the supply and maintenance section of the 12th Air Force.
Did you have any major problems with supply or maintenance with that invasion?
No.
I had plenty of cargo planes I could
go back to Algiers or Tunis and get stuff if I had to have it.
And we got along fine, except for that business of rations and trucks.
We never could get those.
We finally got this ration business straightened out because General Doolittle said, come on, George, let's go up and see Patton.
So we went up, and Jimmy talked to Patton for a few minutes, and we had lunch with him, and got the business of rations straightened out.
General Gay was Patton's chief of staff, and he had lunch with us just before us.
And we got the business of rations straightened out, but I never did get trucks.
I was sold.
disgusted about the truck situation.
I guess I sounded off too much.
General Ridgeway, I think, was taken over from Eisenhower and said, maybe you ought to transfer the troop carrier.
He thought I was getting to the point, I guess, where I was going nuts about this truck situation.
So I got out of supply and maintenance and got into the troop carrier business.
I loved that, being commanding general of the 51st Troop Carrier Wing.
That was a nice job.
Now, exactly what did you do?
Well, we supplied.
We had one squadron of flight nurses.
We transported wounded back to the rear hospitals.
We transported supplies up forward.
We flew supplies over into Yugoslavia to drop to the partisans there, or land and deliver them, and bring out anybody in Yugoslavia that wanted to get back to the American lines.
Did you do any flying yourself or were you just commanding?
I didn't make any of the flights over the Yugoslavia because that was contrary to the policy, higher up policy where the general officer didn't be flying over the lines unless it was necessary.
Right.
That's about all I can think of that we did.
We lost
We had one pilot who overshot Barry and overshot the Catania, Sicily, and took a load of nurses, flight nurses, over and landed in Yugoslavia out of gasoline.
And we were about three weeks getting them back.
The partisans took care of them and kept them out of the hands of the Germans.
We were in touch with my radio all the time.
We finally got him back to Catania, Sicily.
Threw a big party for him with the help of some medical alcohol.
What did you think of Patton?
I liked him.
He was a swashbuckler type of MacArthur.
But when you come with the fighting way, it didn't make him any better than Patton when there was some action out there in the field.
When the war was stalemated, I mean when it was stagnant and we weren't moving far, I didn't care for the way Patton paraded around.
I'm not the type to parade myself around, but he liked it.
just like MacArthur was a big show-off every time he got a chance, but he knew how to deliver when it was necessary.
Now in 1943, you made general officer.
Yeah.
Can you tell me how that came about?
Well, I was commanding about 14-15,000 troops there at Constantine.
forward echelon of the supply and maintenance.
I think I had 15,000 officers and men.
With the 12th Air Force Service Command?

Yeah, and General Spatz came over to see me one time from his headquarters and talked to me a few minutes and looked over at what I was doing and then he said to my Chief of Staff, Colonel Ayling, he said, take a message to

Washington and then he dictated the message it's imperative that Colonel Beverly be promoted to Brigadier General because he's commanding 14,000 personnel in the forward area and should be promoted at once.
I think the same day or the next day why the hardest came through
to make me Brigadier General.
Were you standing right there when he dictated that letter?
Yeah.
What did you feel?
Oh boy, was I happy.
And so was Colonel Haley, my Chief of Staff.
Yeah, I knew I deserved it, but then I wasn't going to stop and wait for it.
In the summer of 1943, you were back in Sicily as the 51st Troop Carrier Wing again.
Were you commanding at them?
Yeah.
Okay, so you were the CEO at that time.
And you went to Rome.
Well, that's after I transferred to the 15th Air Force.

General Twining had the commanding general of the 15th Air Force and a very good friend of mine and I decided I'd like to move on up into Italy and take charge of his service command for him and he very graciously agreed to it and sent his
General Manning back down to take my job, so we just swapped, switched jobs.
And after, when I went...
Exactly what did you do then when you switched jobs?
Well, I just took my headquarters personnel and records and things, put them in a C-47 and flew up to Bari, Italy to take over the
job of commanding general of the 15th Air Force Service Command.
Now, what did they do?
They serviced the 15th Air Force units with supply and maintenance.
I had 23,000 military personnel to about 1,500 officers, I think, the rest
non-commissioned officers and privates.
We had units spread all over South Italy and at every tactical unit, every bomber unit or a fighter unit, why I had a group
Supply and maintenance.
Then I had several depots.
I went forward in the Berry area.
The number one was up at Fujiya, that's north of Berry.
I had one depot down south of Berry.
I had a depot at Berry.
I had three depots.
And...
The service groups, I don't know how many stations there were, but there must have been at least a thousand of these service groups and three depots.
My headquarters unit was a very distant squadron there, about a hundred men.
So you had a tremendous responsibility at that time.
When you went up to Rome, what were the conditions like?
Rome hadn't been touched by bombs.
The Romans were acting like there had never been a war.
They were going around about their business, their living.
Naples was all busted up with bombs, but Rome hadn't been touched by bombs.
People were friendly to us.
We went to see all the sights, of course.
It was just a sightseeing trip, is all it was.
And during the time when you were in Italy, Jack Benny came over and gave a show.
Well, that was in Sicily up there.
Oh, okay, in Sicily.
I was wondering about that.
Yeah, I was in Sicily at that time, I forget.
I think I had the 51st Duke Parade room at that time.
Right, exactly, you're right.
And that's the summer of 43.
Now, did you get these entertainers often?
Did they come often?
Not very often, no.
Let's see, I had, I think twice, I had them,
No, I guess more than that.
Two or three times.
Once in Sicily, in Catania, Sicily.
There was Jack Benny.
He was a bunch.
Another bunch I had in Sicily was Joe Lewis and he was a bunch of fighters.
Came over and put on an exhibition of boxing for us.
Then up in Italy, Marlena Dietrich, I remember she was there, came in.
I guess before a man that was president of Eastern Airlines died not long ago.
He came to see us over at Iran.
You know what I'm talking about.
Anyway, he'd just been rescued from a boat, a rubber boat raft out in the Pacific after about 21 days.
Oh, Rickenbacker.
Rickenbacker, yeah.
He came over to Iran and talked to us.
He gave us a pep talk.
Of course, we were all happy to see him alive.
But as far as I can remember, that's all the entertainers we had.
Well, did these entertainers, did they increase morale?
Did they serve their purpose?
Yeah, yeah.
They did?
Yeah.
Man was very happy to see him.
Did the average troop, you know, just the old private, did he get to see these too?
Yeah, yeah, everybody.
Mm-hmm.
Of course, the next major event is Operation Anvil, the invasion of southern France.
And I was wondering, this was in 1944, in the summer of 1944, about a month after D-Day in Normandy, and I was wondering what your role was in the invasion of southern France.
I was just, still had the same role of supply and maintenance for the 15th Air Force.
They were, the 15th Air Force was
doing some bombing along, I believe it was the Rhone River, along that valley by Leon, down towards Nice.
I was back at Berry.
Were there new problems because of this invasion?
No.
Were there new problems because of D-Day?
Were they taking too much supplies away from the Southern Theater?
No.
By this time we had enough supplies?
We had enough supplies except the things that were in short supply.
The P-51s had a tail wheel and the landing areas we had were so rough the flyers were
land and bust a tailwheel.
I never could get enough tailwheels for the P-51.
I never could get enough 56-inch tires for the bombers who came in on these rough fields.
Maybe land in a sort of a skid, you know, and there goes your tires, and I never could keep them supplied with enough 56-inch tires.

tail wheels with B-51s, and wing and belly tanks with all the fighters because as soon as a fighter plane gets into a fight, the first thing he does is drop his wing tanks and his belly tank and get rid of them so he can maneuver better and he doesn't run the danger of having them
and send her a bullet to go through one of those tanks and blow the whole airplane apart.
So they were dropping their tanks and I was having tanks, U-belly tanks and wingtip tanks shipped over in halves so they could get so many more in an airplane, you know.
And then my depot would put the two halves together and make a tank out of it.
That's the way we had them shipped over.
We were short on bomb sites for part of the time.
Another thing we were short of was fragmentation bombs.
The tactical units just fell in love with those 500 pound frag bombs.
250-pound frag bomb, personnel bombs.
Never could seem to get enough out of the States to keep them happy.
Did you resolve any of these shortages?
I think we finally got enough belly tanks.
How about wheels?
What'd you do about them?
They didn't have the tires?
The wheels would stand up the tires.
I meant the tires.
How about the tires?
I didn't mean wheels.
I meant tires.
If you couldn't get those tires, then what?
You just had to ground them?
Yeah, they'd have to stay on the ground so we could have the tires because we couldn't run the risk of having them blow out on landing.
Sure.
Did you ever get enough tires?
I don't think we did.
No, not while I was there.
I came back in October.
October of 1944, you were requested to transfer United States duty.
Yeah.
Now after you tried so hard to get to the war, why did you want to leave it?
I'd been over there 26 months.
The war was winding down.
It was certainly evident that the Germans couldn't hold out much longer, and I wanted to get on home.
I'm tired of being over there.
And your wife, of course, wasn't with you either.
So you became the Inspector General of Wright-Patterson.
Yeah.
So you're back at Wright-Patterson again.
Yeah.
Did you like that job?
No.
As a matter of fact, I hated inspection of any kind, and that's the reason they made me an inspector,
Some people, you know, just love to ball you out and shake things down and tear things apart.
Inspectors, they are the sons of bitches that give inspectors a bad eye.
When I inspected an outfit, I was there to help them.
So I was just the type they wanted for inspectors.
So I got stuck with it, but I didn't like the work.
I don't like to inspect other people.
Well, you didn't do that very long.
You only did that for about six months.
It took me six months to get out of there and get the job I wanted.
That was commanding general of Kelly Air Force Base in the San Antonio Air Materiel Area.
That's the job I wanted.
Why did you want it?
I just love San Antonio.
I love Texas.
I love to have my own command.
I love to be as far from the throne as possible, and the throne was up at Wright, Patterson, and Dayton.
Here I was down at San Antonio with my own little kingdom, about 23,000 civilian employees and 100 officers to help me.
run the place and I had bases as far as Little Rock and as far as Tucson.
It was all part of my command and I could get out and get away from San Antonio and away from Kelly Field and inspect these once a month, you know.
And I just loved that job.
Would you say that that was the high point of your career?
Yeah.
Because you were your own boss?
Anything after that was at a climax.
What was your question?
Was that because you were your own boss?
Yeah, because I had such a wonderful command there and everybody seemed to like me and think I was doing a good job.
I had some wonderful help.
Were there major changes at Kelly?
that you made during the two years you were there?
No.
I didn't have to make any major changes.
What about as soon as the war was over, one of the big things in the next 18 months was rapid demobilization of the armed forces.
Did that affect Kelly?
Yes.
At one time I had 20,000 airmen and officers in there for discharge.
At one time, 20,000.
My chief of personnel set up an assembly line where we could turn out 500 a day, turn them back to civilian life.
Certain things they had to have.
They had to have a medical exam, and they had to sign these papers, and they had to be given a talk about demobilization or would they join the reserve.
It was quite a job.
to get these boys out, but we were turning out $500 a day there at the last.
I also was making discharge buttons to give each one.
We made $3.5 million of those things at the depot there, $35,000 a day.
So they all made those little honorable discharge buttons?
Yeah, and the thing you put on it.
We turned out 35,000 a day.
That's the reason.
I know that's the reason Eisenhower came down there to inspect me, because he heard about it, and we were turning out a different button from what the Army was getting.
The Army was getting something they called a ruptured duck.
It was put in a lapel, and the Air Force decided that we'd have a separate
this charge button and told me to make three and a half million of them, and that's what we were doing.
I think you are getting thirsty by now.
No, no.
What can I give you some?
Not a thing, thanks.
I could use some ice water.
That's what I thought.
How about you?
Well, you might give me some glass ice water, yeah.
All right.
I'll do that.
Or lemonade, either one.
Now, when Eisenhower came down to inspect, Yeah.
What were your thoughts?
Tell me about his trip down there.
Well, I didn't know what he'd come down there for, but I had a suspicion that he was looking for something.
I showed him all through the shops, you know, and we had everything on a similar line basis, just like a factory in Detroit.
And finally we came to this place where they were making these buttons, and he says, what's this?
I said, these are discharge buttons for the airmen and the officers of the Air Force.
Stop it.
I said, yes, sir.
And that evening after he left, I got on the phone.
I called Wright Patterson, my boss up there.
I forget who it was at that time.
I told him that I had been there and made an inspection.
told me to stop making these discharge buttons.
The next day I got a call from Wright Patterson that said, go right ahead and make them.
So why didn't Eisenhower want you to make them?
Well, he thought, yeah here's this Air Force trying to upstage the Army boys and have a different discharge button and he probably never asked him for his permission.
Probably never asked him for permission to do it, and maybe he's the type that likes to have everybody ask him before they do anything.
Well, what did you think of Eisenhower just in the brief day that you spent with him?
I don't think he was the best general we had during the war, but... Why not?
I guess I didn't know him well enough, maybe.
How efficient was he as far as an inspector?
Well, yeah, he just, he probably didn't know what he was looking at.
I call this service.
How much we owe you?
Why don't you take your shoes off?
No, I'm fine.
I'm just fine.
Are you comfortable?
Yes, I am very comfortable.
You put this on the bill.
Just put this on my tab.
So one of the major operations at Kelly was discharging troops.
Anything else?
New aircrafts?
over a billion dollars worth of property there and a lot of it became surplus when the war was over.

As a matter of fact, six months before the war is where they started shoving in war weary airplanes to me and I had to set up places out in Peyote, Texas and then Hobbs, New Mexico and Tucson, Arizona where we put some of these in mothballs
and set up a detail at Walnut Grove, Arkansas, where we were junking a lot of B-24s.
Were there any problems as far as that was concerned, or was it pretty smooth?
Any what?
Was there any problems?
No problem.
No, with the help I had, I just didn't have any problems
You had superior workers?

I had superior men, I had superior officers, and I had spent most of my nervous and physical energy in finding these officers to help me because I'm naturally lazy and I don't like to, I like to have others do it for me.
One officer I was particularly fond of became a major general
A couple years after I, about a year after I retired.
That was a quality officer.
I got another one, Brigadier General in the reserve.
How about new types of airplanes at this time?
Had the jets started to come out?
No.
Was there any research and development at Kellington?
Oh yeah.
research and development going on all the time, but the jets were coming along, but we didn't have any, I don't think we had any jets in service until about 1950-51 when the P-80, I believe, was...
I bet you, or how are the, now with the war over and the troops coming back and being discharged, how did the people in San Antonio treat them?
They were all jubilant.
They were happy.
I made some talks over the radio about WAI and the main radio station there promoting a separate air force equal to the Army and Navy and I made a journey over to Bryan, Texas to
debate with the Navy file about the separate Air Force.

The Navy apparently were fighting it but uh and then uh when the Amateur Athletic Union had their yearly convention in San Antonio they asked me to make a principal address and uh I talked to them about the separate Air Force and outlined what
We were trying to do what our ideas were on that.
What were your ideas?
Our ideas were we would have a separate Air Force, equal rank with the Army and with the Navy, and the whole thing would be headed by the General Staff, Chief of Staff, which is the present setup.
That's what we were trying for.
And why were you in favor of that?
Well, it's a logical result of what we proved we could do during the Second World War.
We could do it so much better if we had our own commanders and didn't have to go through the Army on it.
And the separate Air Force, why we'd have nothing but Air Force officers over us.
outside of the Chief of the General Staff.
We didn't figure on that much.
We wanted our own separate command.
Was there a lot of resistance from the Army and Navy?
The Navy resisted it.
The Army, I don't think resisted it.
I don't recall that they did.
Maybe they were glad to get rid of us.
Did you feel that you were jeopardizing your career by going out on the line and giving these talks on radio?
No, I never considered my career, jeopardizing my career in anything I did.
I was just as independent as a hog on ice, and I never, never thought of promoting myself by being careful of what I said I did.
Now, during your career, you met a lot of very interesting people, and some of them visited you when you were down in Kelly, like Lord Teder, who was Chief of the Royal Air Force.
Well, I think he was Chief there.
Maybe he was second in command or something.
He was pretty high up in the Royal Air Force.
What were your impressions of him?
Oh, he was just a nice fella and had a nice wife.
He was just on a junket.
And this is when, 1946?
I believe it is.

And during 1946, the British were attempting to get the United States to cooperate as much as possible in the military with them, and of course these are, NATO doesn't come around until 1949, but the British are already eager for a NATO as
As early as 1946.
Did Tedder have anything to say about Anglo-American military cooperation?
No, Tedder didn't have anything to say about it.
He just made a friendly visit.
He knew that I had the largest Air Force depot in the world and he just wanted to see it.
How about General Wainwright?
He was a grand old man.
He and my cousin, Major General Fletcher Sharp, were both taken prisoners by the Japs and mistreated.
The whole time they were prisoners.
Came back physical wrecks.
My cousin died within a year.
I think Wainwright died within a year, maybe a couple of years.
In the meantime, his wife had become an alcoholic.
